INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge, Sierra Club and Jeremy Merklinger

DESCRIPTION: This beautiful rain garden is one of the Rain Garden's to the Rescue program funded by the Erb Family Foundation and coordinated by Friends of the Rouge and Sierra Club Michigan Chapters Great Lakes Program.  This is by far one of the largest in the program and captures runoff from several roof areas.  The beauty of it mirrors the meditative open space at the St. Paul of the Cross Retreat Center.   It's aesthetics match the storm water benefits provided.

INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge, Sierra Club, St. Paul of the Cross Retreat Center

PROJECT_NAME: Christ The King School Rain Garden
DESCRIPTION: This lovely bioretention garden is part of the Rain Garden's to the Rescue storm water mitigation project funded by the Erb Family Foundation and led by Friends of the Rouge with support from Sierra Club Michigan Chapter Great Lakes Program.  These projects are  wonderful examples of the support from the Detroit community for providing nature based solutions that both manage storm water and also improved the quality of life for all residents.
DESIGNER: Cyndi Ross, Friends of the Rouge
INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge, Sierra Club and Christ the King (Katie Little)

DESCRIPTION: The Urban Country Tea House rain garden is part of the Rain Garden's to the Rescue program family of gardens.  This particular garden installation was led by Keep Growing Detroit the RGTTR partner responsible for growing the native plants that are used in garden plantings.  Visitors to the Tea House can learn about GSI and also the Cross Pollinator Corridor being developed just east the this location.  Natural processes abound in this Brightmoor location.
DESIGNER: Friends of the Rouge, Cyndi Ross, and owner Rosalyn Flint
INSTALLER: Keep Growing Detroit, Friends of the Rouge, Rosalyn Flint

PROJECT_NAME: St. Mary's of Redford Rain Garden
DESCRIPTION: This lovely rain garden is part of the Rain Garden's to the Rescue family of gardens funded by Erb Family Foundation.  Friends of the Rouge serves as Project Manager along with Sierra Club Michigan Chapter's Great Lakes Program.  The rain garden sits along the southwest corner of this historic church providing a rainbow of colors for parishioners and those passing by also providing educational opportunities around nature-based solutions to water quality improvements.
DESIGNER: Friends of the Rouge, Cyndi Ross & St. Mary's representatives: Brenda Cornish and Cassandra Logan
INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge, Sierra Club, Cassandra Logan

DESCRIPTION: Gesu's Rain Garden is part of the Rain Garden's to the Rescue GSI program funded by the Erb Family Foundation.  Green Infrastructure involves using nature-based practices like bioswales and rain garden's to soak up storm water that comes off impervious surfaces like roofs and driveways helping to prevent combined sewer overflows.  This, in turn, helps protect the water quality of our lakes and rivers!  The garden's with their beautiful native plants and flowers are a joy to look at as well.!
DESIGNER: Friends of the Rouge, Cyndi Ross and Stephanie Osborn - Gesu Contact
INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge, Sierra Club Michigan Chapter's Great Lakes Program and Gesu Church

PROJECT_NAME: St. Suzanne Cody-Rouge Community Ctr. Rain Garden
DESCRIPTION: This bioretention garden is part of a sustainability initiative funded by the Erb Family Foundation  and led by Detroit Future City.  The initiative is called "Land + Water Works."  It is a coalition of 10 organizations including Friends of the Rouge and Sierra Club. This beautiful garden is one of three that St. Suzanne Cody Rouge Community Resource Center has installed on their inviting campus.  The garden's provide beauty and attract a variety of pollinators.

PROJECT_NAME: Oakland Avenue Urban Farm Rain Garden

The garden is a pilot site for a sensor that detects storm water infiltration installed by U. of Michigan engineering student & Professor Branko Kerkez.

INSTALLER: Friends of the Rouge / Sierra Club / Oakland Avenue Urban Farm (N. Tallman)

Adding a rain garden compliments the theme of sustainability.   It's a pleasure visiting!!

DESCRIPTION: The Hamilton Rainscape emerged from community plans to address blight and stormwater issues. The location and elements of the design were selected through a community engagement process that brought together residents and the designers throughout the development of the project. Residents, ECN staff, and InSite Design Studio came together to create a beautiful open space to gather, redirect stormwater from the street into rain gardens, and serve as an education tool for the community.
INSTALLER: Michigan Hardscape

DESCRIPTION: Rather than replacing spalling concrete with more concrete, The Charles H. Wright Museum of African American History added permeable pavers. We worked with the manufacturer to special order two toned pavers to include the design of a Sankofa symbol, which means ‘go back and get it’ and is derived from the Twi language of Ghana. The word and meaning can best be explained as looking back at the past in order to understand the present and move on to a better future.
INSTALLER: Michigan Hardscape
MAINTAINER: Charles H. Wright Museum of African American History

PROJECT_NAME: Sacred Heart Church Parking Lot GSI Retrofit
DESCRIPTION: Using nature, TNC partnered with the parish to create one of Detroit’s largest GSI projects at a faith-based institution. This retrofit keeps millions of gallons out of the sewer system annually and manages runoff from 1.4 impervious acres. The bioretention gardens add native plants and greenspace to the parking lot and earn the parish a 51% green credit on their drainage charge. Thanks to the Ralph C. Wilson, Jr. & DTE Foundations for funding and to the Garden Club for stewardship and upkeep!
INSTALLER: WCI Contractors
MAINTAINER: Sacred Heart Church (with 3 years of initial support from TNC)
